ften dismissed as superfluous or irrelevant to a contemporary world, this collection of essays directs attention to the ways we laugh, the ways that Austen may make us do so, and the ways that our laughter is conditioned by the form in which Austen writes: comedy. Jane Austen and Comedy invites reflection not only on her inclusion of laughter and humor, the comic, jokes, wit, and all the other topics that can so readily be grouped under the broad umbrella that is comedy, but also on the idea or form of comedy itself, and on the way that this form may govern our thinking about many things outside the realm of Austen’s work. Published by Bucknell University Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aComic, The, in literature. 0aHumor in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aChung, Soha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDempsey, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErwin, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoss, Erin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoss, Erin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKramp, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrueger, Misty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindstrom, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSigler, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978168448081440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781684480814423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781684480814.jpg  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL